      "text": "Theodore Ernest O'Hare -- Theo to everyone who knows him -- is seventeen, restless, and supposed to be reading a chapter about a medieval Italian writer named Boccaccio. The textbook is open on his desk to a painting of young people in a garden, telling stories while the plague rages beyond the walls.\n\n'One hundred tales,' the caption reads. 'Told over ten days.'\n\nTheo's eyelids are heavy. The afternoon light turns golden, then amber, then impossibly warm -- warm like a Tuscan afternoon, warm like bread from a stone oven, warm like a world that hasn't learned yet that it's about to end.\n\nWhen Theo opens his eyes, the desk is gone. The textbook is gone. He is sitting on a marble bench in a church so vast that the ceiling vanishes into shadow. The air reeks of incense and something worse -- something sweet and terrible that he can't name. A bell is tolling. Outside, through the open doors, he can see a city of terracotta rooftops under a pitiless blue sky.\n\nA young woman in a green dress approaches him. She has dark eyes, a sharp chin, and an expression that suggests she has already decided he is either useful or amusing.\n\n'You look lost,' she says. 'Are you here for the service? There's hardly anyone left to attend.' She pauses. 'I'm **Pampinea**. My friends and I are leaving the city today -- the **pestilence** is everywhere. We have a villa in the hills.' She studies him. 'You could come with us. Or you could stay here and take your chances with the dead-carts.'",
