      "text": "Theo sits at the edge of the circle and listens. The tales wash over him -- Ser Ciappelletto's outrageous deathbed performance, Melchisedech's parable of the rings, a Gascon lady who shames a cowardly king with a single sentence.\n\nHe notices something. Every tale is about **wit** -- about the power of the right word at the right moment. The wicked man survives by the cleverness of his tongue. The wise man survives by the cleverness of his parable. Even the woman's rebuke is a kind of weapon forged from language.\n\nAfter the last tale, Dioneo nudges him. 'You're quiet. Thinking deep thoughts?'\n\n'I'm thinking that words matter more here than swords,' Theo says.\n\nDioneo grins. 'Now you're beginning to understand Florence.'",
