      "text": "Filomena is sitting by the fountain, trailing her fingers in the water. She looks up when Theo approaches.\n\n'You noticed it,' she says. 'The tales aren't just entertainment. They're arguments. Ciappelletto's tale asks: can a lie serve the truth? The three rings ask: can tolerance survive in a world that demands certainty?'\n\n'And the Gascon lady?'\n\n'She asks the simplest question of all: when someone with power fails to use it justly, is it enough to shame them with words?' Filomena smiles. 'Boccaccio -- the man who arranged these tales -- believed that stories are how civilized people argue. Not with swords or laws, but with **novelle**. Each tale is a tiny courtroom. The reader is the judge.'\n\nShe looks toward the city on the horizon. The smoke from the plague pyres is visible even here.\n\n'The real question,' she says quietly, 'is whether the judge can bear to hear all the evidence. Some of the tales ahead are not gentle.'",
